  "title": "BCIT Traffic Complexity",
  "description": "The BCIT Traffic Complexity dataset comprises extended neurophysiological recordings during simulated driving tasks designed to assess fatigue-related performance changes. Participants performed continuous driving in a simulator while EEG, eye tracking, and vehicle performance data were collected simultaneously. The study manipulated visual complexity and perturbation frequency to investigate driver fatigue biomarkers and brain-behavior interactions during sustained attention tasks.",
  "methods_description": "Participants performed simulated driving tasks using a Real Time Technologies driving simulator (900 Hz video refresh rate, 100 Hz vehicle data logging). EEG was recorded using BioSemi 64-channel systems with 8 additional channels (4 eye, 2 mastoid) at 2048 Hz sampling rate. Eye tracking was performed using Sensomotoric Instruments REDEYE250. Dependent measures included reaction times to vehicle perturbations, continuous performance metrics (steering angle, lane position, heading error), and subjective fatigue scales (TIFS, KSS, VAS-F). Baseline Driving consisted of 45 minutes of continuous driving in a visually sparse environment, while Traffic Complexity runs included pedestrians and traffic with manipulated visual complexity and perturbation frequency.",
